    <h1>Data Lakehouse vs Data Lake vs Data Warehouse</h1>

    <p>
      These three architectures solve different versions of the same problem.
      This page cuts through the noise: here is what each actually does, where
      it falls short, and which workloads it is genuinely the right fit for.
    </p>

    <h2>Quick Definitions</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Data warehouse:</strong> A centralized database optimized for structured
      analytical queries. Data is loaded through ETL, stored in proprietary columnar
      format, and queried through a proprietary SQL engine.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Data lake:</strong> A storage repository for raw data in open file
      formats on cheap object storage. No enforced schema, no transactions, no consistent
      query interface.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Data lakehouse:</strong> Object storage with open files plus a table
      format layer (Apache Iceberg) that adds ACID transactions, schema enforcement,
      and query optimization on top.
    </p>

    <h2>How They Are Built Differently</h2>

    <Mermaid
      class="my-8"
      diagram={`graph TD
    subgraph WAREHOUSE["Data Warehouse"]
        W1["ETL into proprietary storage"]
        W2["Proprietary SQL engine only"]
        W3["Examples: Redshift, Snowflake (non-Iceberg), Synapse"]
    end
    subgraph LAKE["Data Lake"]
        L1["Raw files in object storage (S3, GCS, ADLS)"]
        L2["No table layer — schema defined at query time"]
        L3["Examples: S3 + raw Parquet, HDFS + raw ORC"]
    end
    subgraph LAKEHOUSE["Data Lakehouse"]
        LH1["Open files in object storage"]
        LH2["Table format: Apache Iceberg (metadata + manifests)"]
        LH3["Catalog: Apache Polaris / Glue / Nessie"]
        LH4["Any engine: Spark, Trino, Dremio, Athena, BigQuery"]
        LH1 --> LH2 --> LH3 --> LH4
    end`}
    />

    <h2>Full Comparison</h2>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr
          ><th>Dimension</th><th>Data Lake</th><th>Data Warehouse</th><th
            >Data Lakehouse</th
          ></tr
        >
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr
          ><td>Storage format</td><td>Open (raw files)</td><td
            >Proprietary columnar</td
          ><td>Open (Parquet + table format metadata)</td></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Storage cost</td><td>Very low</td><td>High</td><td
            >Very low (same object storage)</td
          ></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>ACID transactions</td><td>No</td><td>Yes</td><td
            >Yes (Iceberg)</td
          ></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Schema enforcement</td><td>Read-time only</td><td
            >Write-time strict</td
          ><td>Write-time + safe evolution</td></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>SQL query performance</td><td>Slow (full scans)</td><td
            >Very fast</td
          ><td>Fast (metadata pruning + compaction)</td></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Time travel</td><td>No</td><td>Limited</td><td
            >Yes (Iceberg snapshot history)</td
          ></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Multi-engine access</td><td>Yes (raw files, limited)</td><td
            >No (proprietary API)</td
          ><td>Yes (REST Catalog standard)</td></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>ML / data science</td><td>Good (raw format access)</td><td
            >Difficult (format conversion)</td
          ><td>Good (PyIceberg, Spark, DuckDB)</td></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>AI agent access</td><td>No (no governed interface)</td><td
            >Possible (JDBC/SQL)</td
          ><td>Yes (governed + semantic layer)</td></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Streaming writes</td><td>Yes (raw files)</td><td
            >Limited / expensive</td
          ><td>Yes (Flink + Iceberg, exactly-once)</td></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Governance / RBAC</td><td>S3 bucket-level only</td><td
            >Yes (table/column level)</td
          ><td>Yes (catalog-level RBAC + masking)</td></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Vendor lock-in</td><td>Low</td><td>High</td><td
            >Low (open formats + open catalog)</td
          ></tr
        >
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>When to Use Each</h2>

    <Mermaid
      class="my-8"
      diagram={`flowchart TD
    A["What does your workload look like?"]
    A -->|"Purely SQL analytics, stable schema, moderate volume, one vendor is fine"| B["Data Warehouse"]
    A -->|"Raw ML / data science files only, no SQL or consistency requirements"| C["Data Lake"]
    A -->|"SQL + ML + streaming + AI agents OR multi-engine OR large scale OR vendor independence"| D["Data Lakehouse (Apache Iceberg + open catalog)"]
    D --> E["Choose catalog: Apache Polaris, AWS Glue, Project Nessie"]
    D --> F["Choose engine: Dremio, Trino, Spark, Athena"]`}
    />

    <h2>Migration Triggers</h2>
    <p>
      Teams typically move from a warehouse to a lakehouse when storage costs
      become unsustainable, ML teams need direct access to the same data BI
      uses, or the team wants to add a second query engine without copying data.
    </p>
    <p>
      Teams move from a raw data lake to a lakehouse when data reliability
      problems start causing production incidents, SQL analytics on the lake
      become a requirement, or governance requirements (RBAC, audit, masking)
      can no longer be satisfied with S3 bucket policies.
    </p>

